
TY  - JOUR
T1  - Commercializing the Practice of Voyeurism: How Organizations Leverage Authenticity and Transgression to Create Value
AU  - Ruebottom, Trish
AU  - Buchanan, Sean
AU  - Voronov, Maxim
AU  - Toubiana, Madeline
Y1  - 2020/12/18
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2022/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2019.0210
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2019.0210
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 466
EP  - 488
VL  - 47
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Voyeurism violates dominant moral codes in many societies. Yet, for a number of businesses, including erotic webcam, reality television, slum tourism, and mixed martial arts, voyeurism is an important part of value creation. The success of such businesses that violate dominant moral codes raises questions about value creation that existing theory in management cannot adequately answer. To help advance our understanding, we theorize how businesses commercializing voyeurism create value for audiences. Conceptualizing voyeurism as a social practice, we identify two dimensions of voyeurism?authenticity and transgression?that help create value by generating desirable emotional responses that facilitate a distinctive experience for audiences. However, we further argue that these same dimensions can also hinder value creation by generating undesirable emotional responses that may lead audiences to disengage from the practice. Accordingly, we contend that businesses? ability to deliver value to audiences hinges on effective emotional optimization?efforts to reduce undesirable emotional responses by dampening the authenticity or transgression in the voyeuristic practice, while reinforcing the associated desirable emotional responses. We contribute to the literature by advancing a novel theory of the commercialization of voyeuristic practice. In doing so, we also enrich our understanding of both authenticity and transgression.
AB  - Voyeurism violates dominant moral codes in many societies. Yet, for a number of businesses, including erotic webcam, reality television, slum tourism, and mixed martial arts, voyeurism is an important part of value creation. The success of such businesses that violate dominant moral codes raises questions about value creation that existing theory in management cannot adequately answer. To help advance our understanding, we theorize how businesses commercializing voyeurism create value for audiences. Conceptualizing voyeurism as a social practice, we identify two dimensions of voyeurism?authenticity and transgression?that help create value by generating desirable emotional responses that facilitate a distinctive experience for audiences. However, we further argue that these same dimensions can also hinder value creation by generating undesirable emotional responses that may lead audiences to disengage from the practice. Accordingly, we contend that businesses? ability to deliver value to audiences hinges on effective emotional optimization?efforts to reduce undesirable emotional responses by dampening the authenticity or transgression in the voyeuristic practice, while reinforcing the associated desirable emotional responses. We contribute to the literature by advancing a novel theory of the commercialization of voyeuristic practice. In doing so, we also enrich our understanding of both authenticity and transgression.
