TY  - JOUR
T1  - Fighting with the Fourth Estate: A Theoretical Framework of Organization–Media Rivalry for Narrative Control Following a Transgression
AU  - Hersel, Matt C.
Y1  - 2020/10/30
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2022/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2020.0012
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2020.0012
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 425
EP  - 447
VL  - 47
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In this article, I develop a theoretical framework to explain rivalry for narrative control between members of the media and transgressing organizations. I do so by integrating and advancing key insights from competitive dynamics and crisis management research. The first part of this framework conceptualizes the unique tensions, actions, and reactions that characterize rivalry for narrative control following organizational transgressions and distinguish it from other forms of rivalry. The second part of the framework conceptualizes the role of both journalists? and organizational leaders? perceptions in shaping actions and reactions during rivalry for narrative control. This framework contributes to competitive dynamics research by further conceptualizing how rivalries between dissimilar actors materialize. This framework also broadens research on crisis management following transgressions to account for the potentially rivalrous nature of organization?media relations.
AB  - In this article, I develop a theoretical framework to explain rivalry for narrative control between members of the media and transgressing organizations. I do so by integrating and advancing key insights from competitive dynamics and crisis management research. The first part of this framework conceptualizes the unique tensions, actions, and reactions that characterize rivalry for narrative control following organizational transgressions and distinguish it from other forms of rivalry. The second part of the framework conceptualizes the role of both journalists? and organizational leaders? perceptions in shaping actions and reactions during rivalry for narrative control. This framework contributes to competitive dynamics research by further conceptualizing how rivalries between dissimilar actors materialize. This framework also broadens research on crisis management following transgressions to account for the potentially rivalrous nature of organization?media relations.
